  "prompt": "Is java is a purely object oriented language or no? If not then why?",
  "response": "Java is not considered a purely object-oriented programming (OOP) language. While it follows many object-oriented principles and supports features like classes, objects, inheritance, encapsulation, and polymorphism, it also includes features from procedural programming.\n\nHere are a few reasons why Java is not purely object-oriented:\n\n1. **Primitive Data Types**: Java has primitive data types (such as `int`, `char`, `boolean`, `float`, etc.) that are not objects. These data types can be used directly without the need for an instance of a class, which is a characteristic of procedural programming. In purely object-oriented languages, everything would be represented as objects.\n\n2. **Static Methods and Variables**: Java allows the use of static methods and variables, which belong to the class rather than any instance of the class. This means that you can call a method without creating an object of the class, which again deviates from the pure object-oriented approach.\n\n3. **Non-Object-Oriented Features**: Java includes other features that aren't strictly aligned with the principles of pure OOP, such as static imports and the ability to write standalone methods.\n\nIn contrast, purely object-oriented languages (like Smalltalk) treat everything as an object, with no provision for primitive types or static methods. Therefore, while Java is heavily influenced by object-oriented design and encourages an object-oriented approach, it incorporates elements of other programming paradigms as well, making it not purely object-oriented.",
